</div>
		
		<p>It’s the next stage of a tactic that anti-fascists call “Proactive self-defense,” Vysotsky said.</p>
		
		<p>In 2018, 2019 and 2020, when far-right extremist groups like the Proud Boys announced events in liberal cities like Portland and Berkeley, California, they were <a href="https://theworld.org/stories/2017-09-06/antifa-has-rapid-response-team-targets-alt-right-organizers" target="_blank">met with violent resistance</a> from anti-fascists, some of them organized, who attacked the far-right extremists with bear mace and their fists. </p>
		
		<p>“Far-right demonstrations are almost always either a pretext, or create the conditions to facilitate acts of violence by actors on the far-right,” Vysotsky said. So, he said, anti-fascists respond to threats of violence, and to incursions by right-wing extremists in liberal neighborhoods, with “proactive” violence.</p>
		
		<p>What the Elm Fork John Brown Gun Club did in Roanoke was a stark example of a new phase of armed resistance from the left, he said.</p>
		
		<p>After the social media threats, and after white supremacists and other extremists threatened other LGBTQ events, the Elm Fork John Brown Gun Club decided the Andersons, and the local LGBTQ community, needed their help. </p>
		
		<p>So, in the early hours of Aug. 28, they masked up to protect their identities, and drove to Roanoke with their rifles.  </p>
		
		<div
	class="custom-chapter-marker no-image"
	id="the-scene-inside"
	data-position="top"
	data-layout="body-width"
	
	data-section='' data-section-background-color='#CFCFCF'
	
>
	
	<h2 class="chapter-marker-header"  style="color: #7d1225 !important;">The scene inside </h2>
	
</div>

		
		<p>Hours of video footage shot that day shows practically every detail of what happened at the Barrel Babes Brunch. People who attended described it in interviews. </p>
		
		<p>This is the view of what happened inside the event: </p>
		
		<p>Salem Moon sashayed toward the screaming crowd in a full-length ruby gown glittering with sequins that brushed the top of her size 13-wide stilettos.</p>
		
		<p>Hips swaying, blond wig bouncing and lip-syncing to “Heart to Break” by Kim Petras, the drag queen strutted between tables in full performance mode. Admirers handed her singles, tens, even hundred-dollar bills.</p>
		
		<p>She sauntered to the double doors, threw them open, and was greeted by cheers, cameras and more bills by the crowd on the patio outside.</p>
		
		<p>As the music faded and Salem Moon headed back inside, she bent down and held up her hand to a little girl for a high-five. The child smacked back with gusto.</p>
		
		<p>There were jokes and dances and even a game of musical chairs with audience members. </p>
		
		<p>“Drag is what actually inspired me to want to become a fashion designer,” one participant told the crowd, to huge applause.</p>
		
		<div class="center-container" data-storytelling-component="silent-movie" data-layout="center">
	<video 
		data-src="https://www.gannett-cdn.com/indepth-static-assets/uploads/master/10929001002/558eb4e3-ab46-4dbb-a8d3-0b02bacf917c-drag_inside.mp4" 
		
		muted
		playsinline
		loop
	></video>
	<div class="video-details caption in-depth-image-caption-container">
		
			<span class="video-details attribution in-depth-image-credit"></span>
		</div>
</div>
		
		<p>Bailey Anderson — as Trisha Delish — weaved through the wooden tables in a long-sleeved plum-colored dress and tights, lip syncing to “Magic Dance” by David Bowie. </p>
		
		<p>Salem Moon sang Roar by Katy Perry, dressed in a pink Power Rangers costume. </p>
		
		<p>Rolla Derby —  a female performer who calls herself “The Crayola experience of drag” — sauntered through the crowd in a tight pink dress and cotton candy pink wig, singing along to Gwen Stefani.</p>
		
		<p>Drag queen Nayda Montana lip-synced to “The Best of Both Worlds,” by Hannah Montana, before moving outside and climbing on top of a table, close to where a small child was sitting. For a few seconds, Nayda gyrated her hips. </p>
		
		<p>A man at the table snapped pictures. The child, who had <a href="https://twitter.com/TaylerUSA/status/1564073099015897089?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1564073099015897089%7Ctwgr%5E4ac2f7741ddae4182073e98521e9b7b63c17db75%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.crosstimbersgazette.com%2F2022%2F08%2F30%2Froanoke-restaurant-drag-show-sparks-controversy%2F" target="_blank">been recorded earlier</a> smiling as she watched the performances, was also later captured on video crouched over on the table bench, resting her head on an adult. There were no drag queens around them at the time.</p>
		
		<p>Gretchen Veling watched the dancing and lip-syncing, wondering what all the fuss was about.</p>
		
		<p>Justin Wagley watched the whole show, noting how the drag performers always asked parents for an OK before posing for pictures with a child. </p>
		
		<p>“I never got a funny feeling in my stomach, or a bad taste in my mouth,” he said. </p>
		
		<p>By 3 p.m. the brunch was winding down. A clearly emotional Jay Anderson, who had been rushing around serving customers for hours, took to the mic to thank people for their kindness and support.</p>
		
		<p>That night, he updated the restaurant’s Facebook page:</p>
		
		<p>“We want to thank EVERYONE who showed up today to support our Barrel Babes Brunch. </p>
		
		<figure id='asset-10966117002' class='indepth-image  center-well zoomable' style='--img-height: 3072;--img-width: 4080;' data-layout='center-well'>
	<img src='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg' srcset='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=100 100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=200 200w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=300 300w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=600 600w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=800 800w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=1100 1100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=1500 1500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=2000 2000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=2500 2500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=3000 3000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=3500 3500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=4000 4000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=4500 4500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=5000 5000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/2f43d4ca-6cbe-44c0-8f99-81c262c60fc8-PXL_20220828_181343572.jpg?width=5500 5500w' sizes='(min-width: 768px) 64vw, (min-width: 1024px) 48vw, 100vw' alt='While protesters shouted from across the street, the drag show at Anderson&#39;s went on.' height='3072' width='4080' loading='lazy' />
	<div class="image-zoom__modal-trigger"></div>
	
	<figcaption class="indepth-image__caption">
		While protesters shouted from across the street, the drag show at Anderson&#39;s went on.
		<span class="indepth-image__credit">Courtesy of Steven Monacelli</span>
	</figcaption>
	
</figure>
		
		<p>&#34;Yes, every table was full before we officially opened. Yes, we reached maximum capacity and had a waitlist to get inside. Yes, we ran out of food.”</p>
		
		<p>There are two other things that are known about what happened inside Anderson’s that day.</p>
		
		<p>First, public records show the city determined the business didn’t violate any codes for crowd capacity.</p>
		
		<p>Second, in attendance in the crowd were two inspectors from the Texas Comptroller’s office, the Andersons said. The agency imposes fees on sexually oriented businesses. </p>
		
		<p>How those inspectors came to be summoned is unclear. </p>
		
		<p>Bailey Anderson said they showed up because of complaints from the public. USA TODAY sought records about the comptroller’s involvement under state public records law, but the office declined to release those records, instead forwarding them for review to the state attorney general. </p>
		
		<p>The inspectors, though, apparently found nothing amiss.</p>
		
		<p>That night, in his Facebook post, Jay added:</p>
		
		<p>“Yes, we passed the &#39;no sexual content&#39; inspection from the Texas Comptroller&#39;s Office.”</p>
		
		<div
	class="custom-chapter-marker no-image"
	id="the-scene-outside"
	data-position="top"
	data-layout="body-width"
	
	data-section-background-color='#DFDFDF' data-section=''
	
>
	
	<h2 class="chapter-marker-header"  style="color: #7d1225 !important;">The scene outside</h2>
	
</div>

		
		<p>The scene outside the event was somewhat different.</p>
		
		<p>There, too, people who attended described it in interviews. This scene, too, was extensively documented in video, including scenes released by protesters, by right-wing media outlets, by an independent journalist working the scene that day, and by the Elm Fork John Brown Gun Club.</p>
		
		<p>Outside Anderson’s, spilling from the gray-white sidewalk curbs to the shade trees across the street to the building on the next block, were a lot of people making a lot of noise. </p>
		
		<div class="center-container" data-storytelling-component="silent-movie" data-layout="center">
	<video 
		data-src="https://www.gannett-cdn.com/indepth-static-assets/uploads/master/10929001002/11d0e511-8814-40cd-98c5-450ced7ff693-drag_outside.mp4" 
		
		muted
		playsinline
		loop
	></video>
	<div class="video-details caption in-depth-image-caption-container">
		
			<span class="video-details attribution in-depth-image-credit"></span>
		</div>
</div>
		
		<p>Protesters with signs reading “Stop Sexualizing Children” and “Drag the Queens out of town.” </p>
		
		<p>People on the sidewalk with cameras in each other’s faces.</p>
		
		<p>And standing in front of them all, a line of black-clad gun club members, face masks up in the 97-degree heat. As protesters approached, they cautioned each one to move back. “Stay on your side,” they warned. </p>
		
		<p>The gun club members appeared to be the only people in the crowd openly carrying weapons. </p>
		
		<p>In one video posted on Twitter, three million viewers would eventually watch Clark Magee, a middle-aged man in a red Texas Rangers jersey, rant about pedophiles and claim a pro-drag protester had spat on him. </p>
		
		<p>Two men who had come from nearby Dallas kissed for the cameras and raised a middle finger.</p>
		
		<figure class='indepth-image  center-well zoomable' style='--img-height: 3072;--img-width: 4080;' data-layout='center-well' id='asset-10966129002'>
	<img src='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg' srcset='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=100 100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=200 200w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=300 300w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=600 600w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=800 800w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=1100 1100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=1500 1500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=2000 2000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=2500 2500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=3000 3000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=3500 3500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=4000 4000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=4500 4500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=5000 5000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/29/USAT/ebac25d7-e068-4938-8537-f76f16e83403-PXL_20220828_185643578.jpg?width=5500 5500w' sizes='(min-width: 768px) 64vw, (min-width: 1024px) 48vw, 100vw' alt='The protest against the drag show.' height='3072' width='4080' loading='lazy' />
	<div class="image-zoom__modal-trigger"></div>
	
	<figcaption class="indepth-image__caption">
		The protest against the drag show.
		<span class="indepth-image__credit">Courtesy of Steven Monacelli</span>
	</figcaption>
	
</figure>
		
		<p>One woman screamed at protesters as she drove by.</p>
		
		<p>Kelly Neidert was somewhere across the street keeping away from the main fray. </p>
		
		<p>When the show was over, members of the gun club escorted people to their cars. The protestors melted away. Nobody was shot. Nobody was hurt. That was all. </p>
		
		<p>But beyond the protesters, there had been another category of people in the crowd. </p>
		
		<p>By their own description, they call themselves journalists, though their news outlets are ones focused on outrage. </p>
		
		<p>And their effect on Roanoke was just beginning.</p>
		
		
<section id="chapter18" class="chapter chapter--part-number" data-share-parent='true' data-share-headline='A drag show, a protest and a line of guns: How the battle over one issue is tearing at America' data-canonical='https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/nation/2022/12/31/all-ages-drag-show-roanoke-texas-protest/10929001002/'>
	<div
	class="custom-chapter-marker no-image bg-color sans-serif"
	id="part-four"
	data-position="top"
	data-layout="body-width"
	
	
	
>
	
	<h2 class="chapter-marker-header"  style="background-color: #7d1225;color: #EFEFEF !important;text-align: center !important;">PART FOUR</h2>
	
</div>


</section>
		
		
<section id="chapter19" class="chapter chapter--part-title" data-share-headline='A drag show, a protest and a line of guns: How the battle over one issue is tearing at America' data-canonical='https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/nation/2022/12/31/all-ages-drag-show-roanoke-texas-protest/10929001002/' data-share-parent='true'>
	<div
	class="custom-chapter-marker no-image serif"
	id="the-aftermath"
	data-position="top"
	data-layout="body-width"
	
	
	
>
	
	<h2 class="chapter-marker-header"  style="color: #2a2a2a !important;text-align: center !important;">THE AFTERMATH </h2>
	
</div>


<p><span class="marker">THE DAY AFTER</span> the Barrel Babes Brunch, Mayor Gierisch&rsquo;s email inbox was blowing up.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It was a Drag Queen Pedo GROOMER Event.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why have you allowed your seemingly wholesome city of Roanoke to be overrun with</p>

<p>sexual deviancy in the streets?&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>

<figure data-layout='center-well' id='asset-10960806002' class='indepth-image  rail-container rail-container--small right zoomable' style='--img-height: 258;--img-width: 206;'>
	<img height='258' width='206' loading='lazy' src='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg' srcset='https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=100 100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=200 200w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=300 300w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=600 600w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=800 800w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=1100 1100w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=1500 1500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=2000 2000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=2500 2500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=3000 3000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=3500 3500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=4000 4000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=4500 4500w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=5000 5000w,https://www.gannett-cdn.com/presto/2022/12/28/USAT/8c8df5cc-9278-4c10-8a8f-110fcdc941b1-Scooter_Gierisch.jpg?width=5500 5500w' sizes='(min-width: 768px) 130px, 100vw' alt='Roanoke Mayor Scooter Gierisch' />
	<div class="image-zoom__modal-trigger"></div>
	
	<figcaption class="indepth-image__caption">
		Roanoke Mayor Scooter Gierisch
		<span class="indepth-image__credit">Sarah Glenn</span>
	</figcaption>
	
</figure>

<p>&ldquo;You ought to be absolutely ASHAMED of yourselves for signing off on this. This is TEXAS! The citizens of this great state do NOT approve of the grooming and sexualization of children!&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>The little city, the &ldquo;Unique Dining Capital of Texas,&rdquo; was now being trashed as a haven for child abusers.</p>

<p>For days, day and night, sometimes as late as 9:30 p.m., Gierisch wrote back to the angry emailers. The core of his message:</p>

<p>We did not support this. We tried to stop it. We couldn&rsquo;t find any laws that prevented it. We talked to Jay Anderson. He wouldn&rsquo;t listen. It&rsquo;s not our fault.</p>

<p>City officials talked to the Texas Attorney General&rsquo;s Office. The Denton County District Attorney. Legislators. Anyone they thought could help them prevent this from ever happening again.</p>

<p>Meanwhile, city emails show, Rep. Tan Parker &mdash; a Republican state representative from nearby Flower Mound &mdash; was trying to shepherd the city through its crisis by helping draft a public statement, to be posted on social media and the city website.&nbsp;</p>

